[1] Republic of Serbia: positive serology, bovine, 1st report, RFI
Date: Mon 17 Jun 2013
From: Jaroslaw Kaba <jaroslaw_kaba@sggw.pl> [edited]


1st detection of Schmallenberg virus antibodies in the Republic of Serbia
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Since its emergence in 2011 Schmallenberg virus (SBV) has spilled over into new regions of Europe. At the beginning of 2013, SBV infection was confirmed in Hungary and Slovenia [see comment]. No clinical cases of SBV infection have been, so far, diagnosed in the Republic of Serbia.

Due to the epidemiological situation in the region, a serosurvey to SBV in dairy cattle has been carried out in the Republic of Serbia.

Blood samples were collected between 17 May and 3 Jun 2013 from cows kept in 8 barns located in the northern part of the country (119 cows in total; 4-30 cows in each barn). No cows have been introduced into these barns during at least the last 6 months. All animals had access to pastures and thus could have been exposed to vectors of SBV. The samples were serologically tested on 12 Jun 2013, using ID Screen Schmallenberg virus indirect (IDvet Innovative Diagnostics).

Seropositive cows were detected in 2 barns: 15 (all tested cows) in one barn and 1 cow in the other barn. There was also one barn with one doubtful result.

This is the 1st report of SBV infection from the Republic of Serbia.

[J Bojkovski, A Vasic, N Zdravkovic, N Prokic, M Palamarevic, M Elezovic, S Vakanjac, S Stevanovic-Djordevic
