[2] UK (Scotland): clinical case, bovine
Date: Wed 12 Jun 2013
Source: BBC News [edited]
http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-north-east-orkney-shetland-22877433


A virus spread by midges has been found in a calf born on a farm in Aberdeenshire. Schmallenberg virus (SBV) has been confirmed after the calf -- born to a homebred suckler heifer -- was found to be severely deformed. The disease, first identified on German and Dutch farms, is not thought to pose a risk to humans. A vaccine has been approved by government vets.

In April [2013], there was another confirmed case on a Dumfriesshire farm. Scotland's Rural College (SRUC) advised any farmers who encounter foetal abnormalities, stillbirths, or newborns showing signs of disease to contact their vet.

Last year [2012], a ram from Shropshire was also confirmed with the virus after being transported to Orkney.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
